Inspection, visualisation and analysis of quantitative proteomics data

Introduction

This document provides the details to reproduce the data analysis figures in the course slides.

To be able to execute the code below, you will need to have a working R installation. I also recommend using the RStudio editor. To install the proteomics add-on packages required for this tutorial, you will need to run the following code:

## try http:// if https:// URLs are not supported
source("https://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("RforProteomics", dependencies = TRUE)
biocLite("AnnotationHub")

For a more thorough introduction to R for proteomics, please read the RforProteomics vignette (online or off-line with vignette("RforProteomics") after installing as described above).

We first need to load the proteomics packages:

library("MSnbase")
library("mzR")
library("RforProteomics")
library("pRoloc")
library("pRolocdata")
library("msmsTests")
library("AnnotationHub")

Getting example data

AnnotationHub is a cloud resource set up and managed by the Bioconductor project that programmatically disseminates omics data. I am working on contributing proteomics data.

Normalisation strategies

data(dunkley2006)
boxplot(exprs(dunkley2006))

boxplot(exprs(normalise(dunkley2006, method = "vsn")),
        main = "Variance stabilisation normalisation")
## vsn2: 689 x 16 matrix (1 stratum). Please use 'meanSdPlot' to verify the fit.

boxplot(exprs(normalise(dunkley2006, method = "center.median")),
        main = "Median")

boxplot(exprs(normalise(dunkley2006, method = "quantiles")),
        main = "Quantile")

Heatmap plot

data(msnset)
heatmap(exprs(msnset))

image(msnset)

Hierarchical clustering (with or without heatmap)

data(dunkley2006)
heatmap(exprs(msnset))

hc <- hclust(dist(exprs(dunkley2006)))
plot(hc)

Volcano plots

data(msms.dataset)
e <- pp.msms.data(msms.dataset)
null.f <- "y~batch"
alt.f <- "y~treat+batch"
div <- apply(exprs(e), 2, sum)
res <- msms.glm.qlll(e, alt.f, null.f,div = div)
lst <- test.results(res, e, pData(e)$treat, "U600", "U200", div,
                    alpha = 0.05, minSpC = 2, minLFC = log2(1.8),
                    method = "BH")
res.volcanoplot(lst$tres, max.pval = 0.05,
                min.LFC = 1, maxx = 3, maxy = NULL,
                ylbls = 4)

Abundance histograms

See normalisation above.

From a simpler set (e.g.Deans kdeg/protein/abundance) data, plot a 2d plot with colour as a third scaling variable

data(hyperLOPIT2015)
setStockcol(paste0(getStockcol(), 60))
plot2D(hyperLOPIT2015,
       fcol = "final.assignment",
       cex = exp(fData(hyperLOPIT2015)$svm.score) - 1)
